ch.ecma.csta.logical

Interface LogicalDeviceFeatureServices


  • public interface LogicalDeviceFeatureServices
    A set of services that allow an application to control logical features on a device such as Do Not Disturb and Forwarding.

    Prerequisites Before attempting to use LogicalDeviceFeatureServices, do the following:

    1. Acquire an instance of ServiceProvider by using the ServiceProvider.getServiceProvider method.
    2. Acquire an instance of LogicalDeviceFeatureServices by using the ServiceProvider.getService method.

    Note that not all of the requests and for these services may be supported. In these cases, the request description will state that it is not supported.
    Similarly, not all of the parameters may be supported for a given request, or for any associated events. In these cases, the description of the request (or event) will contain a table of the parameters that are supported.

    Also note that all supported LogicalDeviceFeatureServices requests are also available through AsynchronousServices.sendRequest. Consider using this service when you would like to not block your application while waiting for the response.


    General Information on DeviceID Parameters

    When a DeviceID is passed in the request, it can be either a third party device ID (representing an extension not controlled by this application) or a first party device ID (representing an extension controlled by this application). In either case, the DeviceID can be obtained from DeviceServices or from a previous response or event received in CallControlListener.

    Version:
    4.1
    Author:
    AVAYA, Inc.

      • getAgentState

        GetAgentStateResponse getAgentState(GetAgentState request)
                             throws CstaException

        Provides the agent state at a specified device.

        Example: The following code gives an example of how to use GetAgentState.
        Receiving the response is an indication that the request succeeded. 

          GetAgentState request = new GetAgentState(); 
  // agentExtension is a DeviceID that was retrieved using
  // DeviceServices.getThirdPartyDeviceID(GetThirdPartyDeviceId)
  // this parameter must be a valid agent extension or logical agent id
  request.setDevice(agentExtension);
  GetAgentState request = new GetAgentState();
  // the acdGroup is an optional parameter for EAS environment
  // and is required in a non-EAS environment
  // acdGroup is a DeviceID that was retrieved using 
  // DeviceServices.getThirdPartyDeviceID(GetThirdPartyDeviceId)
  request.setAcdGroup(acdGroup);
  GetAgentStateResponse response = logicalDeviceFeatSvcs.getAgentState(request);
  AgentState agentState = null;
  PendingAgentState pendingState = null;
  boolean agentLoggedOn = false;
  // check whether or not the agent is logged on
  if (response.getAgentStateList().getAgentStateEntry(0).getLoggedOnState()) {
     // agent is logged on, get the state of the agent
     agentLoggedOn = true;
     agentState = response.getAgentStateList().getAgentStateEntry(0)
         .getAgentStateEntryAgentInfo().getAgentInfoItem(0).getAgentState();
         
     // pending agent state
     pendingState = response.getAgentStateList()
         .getAgentStateEntry(0).getAgentStateEntryAgentInfo().getAgentInfoItem(0).getPendingAgentState()
  } else {
    // agent is not logged on
  }
  
 // get the private data from the response
 if (response.getExtensions() != null {
     if (response.getExtensions().getSinglePrivateData() instanceof GetAgentStateResponsePrivateData) {
         // get the private data in the response
         GetAgentStateResponsePrivateData privData = (GetAgentStateResponsePrivateData)response.getExtensions().getSinglePrivateData();
         
         // get work mode and the talk state of the agent
         WorkMode workMode = privData.getWorkMode();
         TalkState talkState = privData.getTalkState();
         
         if ((workMode == WorkMode.AUXWORK) || (!agentLoggedOn)) {
              // get the reason code
              short reasonCode = privData.getReasonCode();
         }
         
         if (talkState == TalkState.ONCALL) {
             // agent could have a pending reason code
             short pendingReasonCode = privData.getPendingReasonCode();
             if (pendingReasonCode > 0) {
                // agent has a pending reason code
             }
         }
     }
 }
        Parameters:
        request - A GetAgentState request that contains a DeviceID of the device on which the agent state is being queried.
        Returns:
        A GetAgentStateResponse Optional private data is available in GetAgentStateResponsePrivateData
        Throws:
        InvalidDeviceIDException - Thrown if an invalid device has been specified.
        SecurityViolationException - Thrown if the user was not authorized to control the specified device.
        OperationException - Thrown if a logic error occurred in the code.
        CstaException - Thrown if an implementation specific error occurred.

      • setAgentState

        SetAgentStateResponse setAgentState(SetAgentState request)
                             throws CstaException
        Supported in AES 6.1 and later.

        Requests a new agent state at a specified device.

        Optional parameters are supported in the private data area with an Avaya-specified SetAgentStatePrivateData object. Example: The following code gives an example of how to use SetAgentState.
        Receiving the response is an indication that the request succeeded. 

          SetAgentState request = new SetAgentState(); 
  // deviceID is a DeviceID that was retrieved  
  // using DeviceServices.getThirdPartyDeviceID(GetThirdPartyDeviceId)
  request.setDevice(deviceID);
  // set the agent state to NOTREADY
  request.setRequestedAgentState(ReqAgentState.NOTREADY);    
  // agent id
  request.setAgentID(acdAgentExtension);
  // agent password
  request.setPassword(password.getBytes());
  // acd group
  // NOTE: that ECMA-269 specifies this is optional, but it is 
  // a required parameter for this implementation.
  // acdGroup is a DeviceID that was retrieved using 
  // DeviceServices.getThirdPartyDeviceID(GetThirdPartyDeviceId)
  request.setGroup(acdGroup);
  
  // send optional private data in the request
  short applicationDefinedReasonCode = 3;
  SetAgentStatePrivateData privData = new SetAgentStatePrivateData();
  privData.setEnablePending(true);
  privData.setReasonCode(applicationDefinedReasonCode);
  privData.setWorkMode(WorkMode.AUXWORK);
  CSTACommonArguments commArgs = new CSTACommonArguments();
  commArgs.setSinglePrivateData(privData);
  request.setExtensions(commArgs);
  
  // send the request and get the response
  SetAgentStateResponse response = logicalDeviceFeatSvcs.setAgentState(request);
  
  // get the private data from the response
  // isPending in the response private data tells us if the change in work mode
  // took effect immediately or if it is pending (the agent is on a call and will
  // go into effect when the call ends)
  SetAgentStateResponsePrivateData privData = 
      (SetAgentStateResponsePrivateData)response.getExtensions().getSinglePrivateData();
  boolean workModePending = privData.getIsPending();
        Parameters:
        request - A SetAgentState request that contains a DeviceID of the device on which the agent state is being changed.
        Returns:
        A SetAgentStateResponse Optional private data parameter is available in SetAgentStateResponsePrivateData
        Throws:
        InvalidDeviceIDException - Thrown if an invalid device ID has been specified or if and invalid password is specified when logging in an agent.
        InvalidObjectStateException - Thrown if an attempt to log in an ACD agent that is already logged in.
        InvalidAgentStateException - Thrown if an attempt to log out an ACD agent who is already logged out, an attempt to log in an ACD agent to a split of which they are not a member, or an attempt to log in an ACD agent with an incorrect password.
        ValueOutOfRangeException - Thrown if the workMode private parameter is not valid for the requestedAgentState or the reasonCode is out of the acceptable range of 0-99.
        ObjectNotKnownException - Thrown if an invalid on-PBX station was specified for the ACD agent in device, the group or device parameters were NULL.
        InvalidFeatureException - Thrown if the feature is not available for the group, or the enablePending feature is not available for the administered switch version.
        InvalidObjectTypeException - Thrown if the reason code is specified, but the workMode is not AUXWORK, or requestedAgentState is not LOGGEDOFF.
        StateIncompatibilityException - Thrown if A work mode change was requested for a non-ACD agent, or the Agent station is maintenance busy or out of service.
        InvalidObjectStateException - Thrown if the Agent is already logged into another split.
        ResourceBusyException - Thrown if an attempt to log in an ACD agent that is currently on a call.
        SystemResourceAvailabilityException - Thrown if the request cannot be completed due to lack of available switch resources.
        SecurityViolationException - Thrown if the user was not authorized to control the specified device.
        OperationException - Thrown if a logic error occurred in the code.
        CstaException - Thrown if an implementation specific error occurred.

      • setForwarding

        SetForwardingResponse setForwarding(SetForwarding request)
                             throws CstaException
        Turn on or off the Forwarding feature at the specified device. The forwarding feature is used to redirect calls that arrive at a specified device to an alternate destination.

        Example: The following code gives an example of how to use SetForwarding.
        Receiving the response is an indication that the request succeeded. 

         SetForwarding request = new SetForwarding(); 
 // deviceIDToSetFeature is a DeviceID that was retrieved  
 // using DeviceServices.getThirdPartyDeviceID(GetThirdPartyDeviceId)
 request.setDevice(deviceIDToSetFeature);
 // set the forwarding type,
 // only forwardImmediate is currently supported
 request.setForwardingType(ForwardingType.FORWARDIMMEDIATE);
 // enable forwarding
 request.activateForward(true);
 // set the device to which calls are forwarded
 // deviceIDToForwardCallsTo is a DeviceID that was retrieved  
 // using DeviceServices.getThirdPartyDeviceID(GetThirdPartyDeviceId)
 request.setForwardDN(deviceIDToForwardCallsTo);
 SetForwardingResponse response = logicalDeviceFeatSvcs.setForwarding(request);
        Parameters:
        request - A SetForwarding request that contains a DeviceID of the device on which the do not disturb feature is being set.
        Returns:
        A SetForwardingResponse
        Throws:
        InvalidDeviceIDException - Thrown if an invalid device ID has been specified.
        SubscribedResourceAvailabilityException - Thrown if the Call Forwarding feature is not administered on the specified device.
        SecurityViolationException - Thrown if the user was not authorized to control the specified device.
        OperationException - Thrown if a logic error occurred in the code.
        CstaException - Thrown if an implementation specific error occurred.

      • getAcdSplit

        GetAcdSplitResponse getAcdSplit(GetAcdSplit request)
                         throws CstaException
        Supported in AES 6.1 and later.

        The Get ACD Split service is a private request that provides the number of ACD agents available to receive calls through the split, the number of calls in queue, and the number of agents logged in. The number of calls in queue does not include direct-agent calls.

        Example: The following code gives an example of how to use GetAcdSplit.
        Receiving the response is an indication that the request succeeded. 

         GetAcdSplit request = new GetAcdSplit(); 
 // acdSplitExtension is a DeviceID that was retrieved  
 // using DeviceServices.getThirdPartyDeviceID(GetThirdPartyDeviceId)
 request.setDevice(acdSplitExtension);
 GetAcdSplitResponse response = logicalDeviceFeatSvcs.getAcdSplit(request);
 // get agent data from the response
 int numAgentsLoggedIn = response.getAgentsLoggedIn();
 int numAvailAgents = response.getAvailableAgents();
 int numCallsInQueue = response.getCallsInQueue();
        Parameters:
        request - A GetAcdSplit request that contains a DeviceID for the ACD Split extension for which the Get ACD Split service is requested.
        Returns:
        A GetAcdSplitResponse
        Throws:
        InvalidDeviceIDException - Thrown if an invalid device ID has been specified.
        SecurityViolationException - Thrown if the user was not authorized to control the specified device.
        OperationException - Thrown if a logic error occurred in the code.
        CstaException - Thrown if an implementation specific error occurred.

      • getAgentLogin

        GetAgentLoginResponse getAgentLogin(GetAgentLogin request)
                             throws CstaException
        Supported in AES 6.1 and later.

        The Get Agent Login Service is a private request that provides the extension of each ACD agent logged into the specified ACD split. This service is unlike most other services. After returning the response, the service returns a sequence of AgentLoginExtensionEvent CSTAPrivateEvent events. Each agentLoginExtensionEvent contains a list. The list contains the number of extensions in the message and up to 10 extensions of ACD agents logged into the ACD split. The entire sequence of agentLoginExtensionEvent may contain a large volume of information (up to the maximum number of logged-in agents allowed in an ACD Split). The final agentLoginExtensionEvent specifies that it contains zero extensions and the isFinalResponse parameter is set to true which serves to inform the application that no more messages will be sent in response to this query.

        The agentLoginExtensionEvent events are published to the Logical Device Feature Services listener that is on the same session that issues the getAgentLogin request. A Logical Device Feature Services Listener must be added for the ACD Split extension before the getAgentLogin request is made. The listener must be added to the session that will issue the getAgentLogin request. Only the listener on the session that issued the request will receive the agentLoginExtensionEvent.

        Example: The following code gives an example of how to use GetAgentLogin.
        Receiving the response is an indication that the request succeeded. 

          // acdSplit is a DeviceID that was retrieved  
  // using DeviceServices.getThirdPartyDeviceID(GetThirdPartyDeviceId)
  // add listener to receive the events
  LogicalDeviceFeatureServicesListener ldfsListener = new LogicalDeviceFeatureServicesListenerImpl();
  monitoringServices.addLogicalDeviceFeatureListener(acdSplit, ldfsListener);
 
  GetAgentLogin request = new GetAgentLogin();
  request.setDevice(acdSplit);
  GetAgentLoginResponse response = logicalDeviceFeatSvcs.getAgentLogin(request);
  
  // end of the code example for the request/response
 
  // following is example of the event in the Logical Device Feature Services Listener
  // look for events on LogicalDeviceFeatureServicesListenerImpl
  public void agentLoginExtensionEvent(AgentLoginExtensionEvent event) {
       System.out.println("Received agentLoginExtension event" );   
       AgentLoginExtensionList agentList = event.getAgentLoginExtensionList();
       for (int x =0; x < agentList.getAgentExtensionCount(); x++) { 
           String agent = agentList.getAgentExtension(x);
           System.out.println("AgentExtension in event=" + agent);
       }
       System.out.println("isFinalResponse=" + event.getIsFinalResponse());   
       if (event.getIsFinalResponse()) {
           try {
               cleanup();
           } catch (CstaException e) {
               e.printStackTrace();
           }
       }
   }
        Parameters:
        request - A GetAgentLogin request that contains a DeviceID of the device on which the Get Agent Login service is requested.
        Returns:
        A GetAgentLoginResponse
        Throws:
        InvalidDeviceIDException - Thrown if an invalid device ID has been specified.
        SecurityViolationException - Thrown if the user was not authorized to control the specified device.
        OperationException - Thrown if a logic error occurred in the code.
        CstaException - Thrown if an implementation specific error occurred.

      • getCallLinkageData

        GetCallLinkageDataResponse getCallLinkageData(GetCallLinkageData request)
                                       throws CstaException
        Supported in AES 6.1 and later.

        The Get Call Linkage Data Service is a private request that responds with the Call Linkage Data for a normal callID. This query may be requested at anytime during the life of a call.

        Note that Communication Manager refers to this as the Universal Call ID (UCID).

        Example: The following code gives an example of how to use GetCallLinkageData.
        Receiving the response is an indication that the request succeeded. 

         GetCallLinkageData request = new GetCallLinkageData(); 
 // connId is a ConnectionID that was discovered from a previous response or event.
 // Two common sources are CallControlListener.delivered(DeliveredEvent)
 // or SnapshotServices.snapshotDevice(SnapshotDevice)
 // The call parameter is set to the ConnectionID of a call
 // (i.e. the normal callID of a call), the deviceID is ignored.
  request.setCall(connId);
 GetCallLinkageDataResponse response = logicalDeviceFeatSvcs.getCallLinkageData(request);
 // get the call linkage data
 String uniqueCallId = response.getCallLinkageData().getGlobalCallData().getGlobalCallLinkageID().getGloballyUniqueCallLinkageID();
        Parameters:
        request - A GetCallLinkageData request that contains a ConnectionID of the call on which the Get Call Linkage Data service is requested.
        Returns:
        A GetCallLinkageDataResponse
        Throws:
        InvalidCallIDException - Thrown if an invalid Call ID has been specified.
        SecurityViolationException - Thrown if the user was not authorized to control the specified device.
        OperationException - Thrown if a logic error occurred in the code.
        CstaException - Thrown if an implementation specific error occurred.
